  <div class="container">
    <h1>Containers from 30,000 Feet</h1>
    <h2>The Evolution of Virtualization</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Underutilized Servers:</strong> Traditionally, servers operated at only 5-10% capacity.</li>
      <li><strong>Virtual Machines (VMs):</strong> Introduced by VMWare, allowing multiple servers to run within one.</li>
      <li><strong>Limitations:</strong> VMs require their own OS, consuming resources and needing patching, monitoring, and licenses.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>The Container Revolution</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Containers share a single host OS, minimizing resource usage.</li>
      <li>They are fast to start, ultra-portable, and easy to move across platforms.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Similar Technologies</h2>
    <blockquote>
      "There are many OS virtualization technologies similar to containers that pre-date Docker and modern containers."
    </blockquote>
    <ul>
      <li>Examples include BSD Jails, Solaris Zones, and IBM's System/360 on the mainframe.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Containers Across Platforms</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Windows Containers:</strong> Available on Windows 10 and Windows Server 2016.</li>
      <li><strong>Cross-Platform Considerations:</strong> Linux containers can run on Windows using Docker Desktop.</li>
      <li><strong>Mac:</strong> No native Mac containers, but Linux containers can be run via Docker Desktop.</li>
    </ul>
    
    <footer>Designed for GitHub-friendly presentation using HTML and CSS.</footer>
